# STORY.md — The Docks

## Backstory & Setting

---

### The City

They call it **The Docks** — though the shipping container cranes haven't worked in fifteen years. Now they just rust against the sky like skeleton fingers pointing at nowhere. The waterfront stretches for miles: abandoned warehouses, collapsed piers, streets that flood when the tide comes in. Used to be the heartbeat of the city's economy. Now it's where the city dumps its problems.

Welcome home.

---

### The Player

You just got out. Three years in state correctional — not for anything serious, just bad luck and a bad lawyer. Possession with intent. The kind of charge that ruins your life but doesn't make you a king. You'd do the time, get out, and find the world had moved on without you.

Your apartment's gone. Your girl's gone. Your "crew" dissolved the moment your cell door clicked shut. Old friends suddenly don't return calls. The streets you grew up on are run by people who've never seen you before.

But here's what they don't know: you learned things inside. You met people. You figured out how the real game works. And you've got nothing left to lose.

---

### The Goal

You start with nothing but a burner phone, a duffel bag of clothes, and the phone number of a connect who sells product below market rate. The Docks are carved up between twelve factions — each one ruling their slice like feudal lords. They're all at each other's throats. That's your opening.

Your goal isn't just to survive. It's to own this place. Every pier, every warehouse, every dilapidated apartment building where the rent's three months late and nobody asks questions. You want to look at a map and see your name on half of it.

You want to be the one they fear.

---

### The Tone

This is noir. Not the cartoonish violence of action movies — the slow, grinding horror of life at the bottom where every choice costs something. You won't be a hero. You'll be a survivor. Sometimes you'll do terrible things to people who probably deserved it. Sometimes you'll do terrible things to people who didn't.

The money's good. The power's real. But it eats you from the inside, and there's no way to spit it out.

---

### The World

**The Docks** is a place of contrasts: old-world architecture crumbling alongside modern greed, where waterfront mansions abandoned by shipping magnates now house the families of the men who poisoned this place. The fog rolls in off the harbor most nights, and the streetlights flicker with failing electronics. Neon signs for dead businesses buzz overhead.

The police don't come here. The politicians don't talk about it. It's a place the rest of the city pretends doesn't exist.

And that's exactly why it thrives.

---

### Key Locations

| Location | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| **The Harbor** | Abandoned piers, fishing boats, hidden coves for smuggling |
| **Ironworks** | Old shipyard, now chop shops and auto body shops |
| **The Flats** | Low-income housing, mostly intact, fiercely territorial |
| **Old Town** | Victorian architecture, gambling dens and speakeasies |
| **The Maw** | Industrial district, warehouses, tunnels beneath everything |
| **Skid Row** | The worst of the worst, where the desperate go to disappear |

---

### The Money

Product moves. That's the simple truth of The Docks. But what kind of product — and who controls the supply — that's what makes or breaks a king. The twelve factions have carved up the trade between them, and there's always room for someone hungry enough to take a slice.

You start small. Buy low, sell high. Build a reputation. Then build an empire.

The question is: how far are you willing to go?

---

*This is your city now. Go take it.*
